---
description: Prefer claude-context semantic search over native grep, ripgrep, and find for code discovery
globs: "**/*"
alwaysApply: true
---

Code search: For any code search that is conceptual or discovery-oriented (questions like "where is X", "how does Y work", "show me the path that handles Z"), prefer the claude-context MCP `search_code` tool over native `grep`, `ripgrep`, `find`, or read-then-scan workflows. Native `grep` and `ripgrep` are still correct when the query is a literal string match (an exact error message, a specific symbol name, a regex with anchors), when every occurrence is needed rather than ranked candidates, when precise line numbers are required, when the repo is small enough to read directly, or when claude-context returns no useful results.

Indexing prerequisite: claude-context only works against indexed codebases. If `search_code` returns a "not indexed" error, call `index_codebase` with the absolute repository root and `splitter: "ast"`, confirm progress with `get_indexing_status`, and retry the search once status is `completed`. Re-index only when the working tree has changed materially since the last index, since indexing the same repo cost real model compute on the local broker.

Tool arguments: Pass the absolute path to the repository root on every call. Phrase queries as natural-language descriptions of intent, not as literal regexes or symbol names (good: "where does the broker authenticate XPC peers"; bad: "authenticatePeer\\("). Use `extensionFilter` to constrain by file type when relevant. Leave `limit` at the default unless the top results miss the answer.

Subagents: When launching Task subagents, explore agents, or generalPurpose agents that need to read or search code, instruct them in their prompt to use claude-context `search_code` as the primary search tool and to fall back to native `grep` or `ripgrep` only for literal matches or when claude-context returns nothing useful. Include the absolute repository path in the prompt so the subagent does not have to infer it.

Result handling: Treat claude-context results as ranked candidates, not authoritative locations. Read the cited file regions with the Read tool to confirm semantics before acting on them, since the indexed chunks may be stale relative to the working tree if files have changed after the last index.
